  "success": true,
  "output": "## Performance Analysis ‚Äî jobsquare\n\nThis is a pure-Python async scraper (no React/frontend exists in this repo, so I've substituted \"redundant computations in the hot loop\" for that category). 114 sources are configured, several with `max_pages` up to 40√ó10=400 jobs each, so a full run can move several thousand `Job` objects through `pipeline.py` ‚Üí `filters.py` ‚Üí `store.py`. Findings below are ranked by actual impact at that scale.\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern ‚Äî `store.py:55-74` (`Store.diff`)\n\nEvery job triggers its own `SELECT`, then its own `INSERT`/`UPDATE` ‚Äî one SQLite round trip per row instead of a batch operation. With thousands of jobs per run this is thousands of separate statement executions inside a single transaction.\n\n```python\n# current ‚Äî O(n) individual queries\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    ...\n```\n\nFix: one bulk `SELECT ... WHERE key IN (...)` (chunked to stay under SQLite's default 999-parameter limit) to build a `{key: content_hash}` map, then split into insert/update batches and use `executemany`:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    existing = {}\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 900):\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 900]\n        q = f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({','.join('?' * len(chunk))})\"\n        existing.update({r[\"key\"]: r[\"content_hash\"] for r in self.conn.execute(q, chunk)})\n\n    new, changed, touched = [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = existing.get(job.key)\n        if h is None:\n            new.append(job)\n        elif h != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job)\n        else:\n            touched.append((now, job.key))\n\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    if new:\n        cur.executemany(\"INSERT INTO jobs (...) VALUES (...)\", [{**j.to_row(), \"now\": now} for j in new])\n    if changed:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET ... WHERE key=:key\", [{**j.to_row(), \"now\": now} for j in changed])\n    if touched:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", touched)\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nNot urgent at the current DB size (~348KB), but it's a linear-with-jobs cost that grows every time you add sources.\n\n### 2. Redundant computation ‚Äî regex recompiled per job (`filters.py:11-27`)\n\n`_compile(exclude)` and `_compile(include)` are called from inside `match()`, which runs **once per job**. Every job re-compiles the same include/exclude keyword patterns from scratch ‚Äî O(jobs √ó keywords) compilations instead of O(keywords).\n\n```python\n# current: filters.py:44-55 ‚Äî match() is called per-job, and it recompiles every time\ndef filter_jobs(jobs, rules):\n    ...\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=rules.get(\"include_keywords\"), ...)]\n```\n\nFix ‚Äî compile once outside the loop:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = ...\n    include_re = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude_re = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    locations = rules.get(\"locations\")\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include_re, exclude_re, locations, cutoff)]\n\ndef match(job, include_re, exclude_re, locations, cutoff) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude_re and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude_re):\n        return False\n    if include_re and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include_re):\n        return False\n    ...\n```\n\nCheap fix, real savings ‚Äî with a handful of keywords across a few thousand jobs this is thousands of avoidable `re.compile` calls per run.\n\n### 3. Wasteful deep-copy in `Job.to_row()` ‚Äî `models.py:71-75`\n\n```python\ndef to_row(self) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    d = asdict(self)      # deep-copies EVERY field, including `raw`\n    d.pop(\"raw\", None)    # ...then immediately throws the copy away\n```\n\n`dataclasses.asdict()` recursively `copy.deepcopy()`s nested containers. `raw` holds the full parsed API payload for most fetchers (`raw=j` in `parse_lever`, `parse_ashby`, `parse_recruitee`, `parse_workable`, `parse_greenhouse`, `parse_smartrecruiters` ‚Äî some of these can carry full posting metadata). `to_row()` is called once per new/changed job in `_insert`/`_update`, so every persisted job pays for a deep copy of data it's about to discard.\n\nFix ‚Äî skip `raw` explicitly instead of copying then popping:\n\n```python\nfrom dataclasses import fields\n\ndef to_row(self) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    d = {f.name: getattr(self, f.name) for f in fields(self) if f.name != \"raw\"}\n    d[\"key\"] = self.key\n    d[\"content_hash\"] = self.content_hash\n    return d\n```\n\n### 4. Uncached property recomputation ‚Äî `models.py:60-69`\n\n`content_hash` (sha256) and `posted_dt` (datetime parsing) are plain `@property`s, recomputed on every access. `content_hash` is currently read twice per changed job (once in the future `diff()` comparison, again inside `to_row()`), and `posted_dt` gets re-parsed anywhere it's read (filter cutoff check, any future sort/display code). Cheap per-call, but avoidable:\n\n```python\nfrom functools import cached_property\n# Job uses `slots=True` ‚Äî add explicit slots for the cached fields, or\n# switch to manual memoization in __post_init__ since frozen slotted\n# dataclasses don't support cached_property out of the box:\n@dataclass(slots=True)\nclass Job:\n    ...\n    _content_hash: str | None = field(default=None, repr=False, compare=False)\n\n    @property\n    def content_hash(self) -> str:\n        if self._content_hash is None:\n            blob = \"|\".join((self.title, self.location, self.url, self.department))\n            object.__setattr__(self, \"_content_hash\", hashlib.sha256(blob.encode()).hexdigest()[:16])\n        return self._content_hash\n```\nLow priority ‚Äî only worth it if profiling shows it matters; sha256 of a short string is ~microseconds.\n\n### 5. Sequential pagination where parallelism is possible ‚Äî `fetchers.py`\n\n`fetch_workday` (line 447) is the one fetcher that learns the **total** count from the first page's response (`data.get(\"total\", ...)`) but still pages strictly sequentially afterward. Amazon/Microsoft/Netflix/Google/TwoSigma/Optiver genuinely can't parallelize (they stop on first empty page, no total known), so those are fine as-is. For Workday specifically:\n\n```python\nasync def fetch_workday(client, source):\n    ...\n    first = await _get_json(client, cxs, method=\"POST\", json={..., \"offset\": 0}, ...)\n    total = first.get(\"total\", 0)\n    postings = first.get(\"jobPostings\", [])\n    remaining_offsets = range(page_size, min(total, 5000), page_size)\n    pages = await asyncio.gather(*(\n        _get_json(client, cxs, method=\"POST\", json={..., \"offset\": off}, ...)\n        for off in remaining_offsets\n    ))\n    for data in [first, *pages]:\n        postings_all.extend(data.get(\"jobPostings\", []))\n```\nThis turns N sequential round trips into 1 + concurrent(N-1) for large Workday boards (NVIDIA-scale employers). `fetch_all`'s outer semaphore (`concurrency=8`) already caps overall concurrency, so this needs its own local semaphore to avoid blowing past that budget within one source.\n\n### 6. Blocking I/O inside the async pipeline ‚Äî `pipeline.py:44`, `notify.py:105-109`\n\n`dispatch(new, changed)` is called synchronously from inside `async def run()`. Its notifiers use blocking `httpx.post`/`smtplib` calls (Slack, webhook, email, Twilio ‚Äî each with up to a 15s timeout). Nothing else is running concurrently at that point in this script today, so it's not causing a bug ‚Äî but it does mean a slow/hanging notifier (e.g. SMTP timeout) serializes after fetch/filter instead of overlapping, and it's a foot-gun if `dispatch` is ever called earlier in the pipeline. If you want it non-blocking:\n\n```python\nawait asyncio.to_thread(dispatch, new, changed)\n```\n\n### Caching opportunities worth adding\n\n- **Meta's scraped `lsd`/`__spin_*` tokens** (`fetch_meta`, `fetchers.py:541-546`) are re-scraped from the careers HTML page on every run. If you ever run the pipeline more than once in quick succession (e.g. testing), caching these tokens for a few minutes would save one full-page HTML fetch.\n- **No HTTP caching/conditional requests** (`If-None-Match`/`If-Modified-Since`) anywhere ‚Äî most of these ATS JSON APIs don't support it, but Greenhouse/Lever do support ETags on some endpoints; worth checking if you want to cut bandwidth on frequent scheduled runs (the 12h cron mentioned in recent commits).\n\n### Memory leaks\n\nNone found ‚Äî this is a short-lived CLI/cron process (`cli.py` / `agent.py`), the `httpx.AsyncClient` is properly closed in `fetch_all`'s `finally` block (fetchers.py:785-787), and `Store` is used as a context manager everywhere. No long-lived caches or unbounded growth structures exist. Not applicable to this codebase's lifecycle.\n\n---\n\n**Priority order if you want to act on this**: #1 (N+1 diff) and #2 (regex recompilation) are the cheapest, clearest wins ‚Äî both are small, localized diffs. #3 (deep-copy) matters more as your `raw` payloads get richer. #5 is a nice-to-have only if a Workday-backed employer with a huge board is slow in practice.\n",
